show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.

info.info_how_calculated: Estimated number of people for whom poverty status is determined, whose annual income falls below 100% of the federal poverty level, divided by the number of people for whom poverty status is determined; expressed as percent.

Neighborhoods are ranked according to the percent of people whose annual income falls below 100% of the federal poverty level. Rankings are then divided into 3 approximately equal groupings of low, medium and high poverty.

link_data_node.linkDataPagetext: The "Link Data" function shows associations between environmental health data at the neighborhood level using <a href="http://a816-dohbesp.nyc.gov/IndicatorPublic/Glossary.aspx?#Scatterplot" target="_blank">scatterplots.</a> The points represent x and y values for each NYC neighborhood. The pairs of indicators available for scatterplots were chosen because previous research suggests that one may either directly or indirectly cause or contribute to the other. Because the data being charted are <a href="http://a816-dohbesp.nyc.gov/IndicatorPublic/Glossary.aspx?#Ecological_Study" target="_blank">ecological</a> and not individual level, and because many factors contribute to the health of a population or environment, the patterns seen in these charts do not necessarily represent the underlying causal relationship.

Compare.x_axis_title: Fall-related hospitalizations among older adults - Age-Specific Rate (per 100,000 population 65 yrs and older) 2012-2014

info.info_how_calculated: Age-specific rates were calculated per 100,000 population 65 years and older. Numerator consists of NYC hospital admissions related to falls among adults aged 65 years and older, identified using ICD10-CM codes: V00.1(1-5,8)1; V00.2(1,2,8)1; V00.3(1,2,8)1; V00.8(1-3,9)1; W00.0-W15; W16.0(1-3)2; W16.1(1-3)2; W16.3(1-3)2; W16.42x; W16.5(1-3)2; W16.6(1,2,7)2; W16.7(1,2)2; W16.8(1-3)2; W16.92x, W17; W18.1(1,2)x; W18.2xx; W18.3(0,1,9)x; W19. Only live discharges and initial encounters are included. All figures include NYC residents only.
info.info_source: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS) inpatient data, 2016, updated January 2018. NYC DOHMH population estimates, modified from US Census Bureau interpolated intercensal population estimates, 2016, updated September 2017.

Compare.graph_title: Neighborhood  Children under 6 years with elevated blood lead levels by NTA (Preliminary Data) by Poverty

info.x_axis_title_reg: Children under 6 years with elevated blood lead levels by NTA
info.info_name: Children under 6 years with elevated blood lead levels by NTA
info.info_how_calculated:
Number of children under 6 years of age tested with blood lead levels (BLL) 5 mcg/dL or greater, divided by the total number of children under 6 years of age who were tested; expressed as cases per 1,000 tested. While children can receive more than one test during the calendar year, for this measure children are only counted once per year using the highest confirmed blood lead level during the calendar year. If the child does not have a confirmed test in a given year, the child’s blood lead level is based on the highest capillary or unknown test type. Read more about different measures used by the Health Department for surveillance of childhood lead poisoning.

  • For the purpose of providing data for small geographic areas, multiple years of data were combined to get sufficient numbers of observations to make more reliable estimates for a greater number of neighborhood tabulation areas (NTAs). 
  • Annual numbers and rates of children under 6 years of age with elevated blood lead levels at the citywide, borough, and United Hospital Fund neighborhood level are available here.
info.info_source: New York City Healthy Homes Program
